<TITLE> Govt reluctant to pressure businesses: Faruq </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jan 13 (bdnews24.com) - The commerce minister has said the government does not want to do business or put pressure on businesses, instead it wants to assist them. Faruq Khan said strengthening the Trading Corporation of Bangladesh, the government's trading arm, would not be needed if the businesses played active roles. His comment came after business leaders had pressed him for strengthening the TCB. "The government is enough faith in businesses," said on Tuesday when teams of Bangladesh Knitwear Manufacturers' and exporters' Association and Metropolitan Chamber of Commerce and Industry met him. Faruq said the government would enforce the consumer rights protection ordinance the ordinance. It would never allow the ordinance to be made ineffective. Legal steps would be taken against those who might try to stop the enforcement of the law, he warned MCCI president Abdul Hafiz Chowdhury proposed that the minister allowed maximum three labour organisations in Chittagong port. "We are scared because some labour organisations and trade unions were trying to be active again." "If they become active again, the reforms programmes what we have already started will be stagnant." He asked the minister to keep law and order, political stability normal for businesses to flourish. BKMEA president Fazlul Haq proposed more cash subsidies to knitwear sector. "We have to watch for the global economic recession as our country also may get affected," said Haq. The minister listened to the business leaders and assured them of steps. Commerce Secretary Firoz Ahmed and senior officials of the ministry were present at the meetings. bd
